To determine the number of sides in a regular polygon based on the relationship between the measures of its interior and exterior angles, let us denote \( N \) as the number of sides and use the fact that each interior angle (\( I \)) plus its corresponding exterior angle (\( E \)) equals \( 180^\circ \) since together they form a straight line. Given \( I = 6.5E \), we write the following equations:\[\begin{align*}
I &= 180^\circ - E,\tag{$1$} \\
I &= 6.5E. \tag{$2$}
\end{align*}\]Substituting ($2$) into ($1$), we get: \[ 6.5E = 180^\circ - E \]Solving for \( E \), yields: \[ 7.5E = 180^\circ \]So: \[ E = \frac{180^\circ}{7.5} = 24^\circ.\]Since every central angle of a regular polygon divides the full rotation (360 degrees) equally among \( N \) equal arcs formed by consecutive vertices around the shape's center—as noted earlier
